    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-07T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-07T06:00:00-05:00" n="601"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d601">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/440: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-07T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 7, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 7—7:29 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>344. My 341, July 6, noon.<note n="45" xml:id="d601fn45">Not printed.</note>
                    Translation of the text of the American note appears in the press this morning
                    in news despatches from New York which also state that the note is generally
                    regarded as a refusal to interfere in any way. It is further reported that in
                    reply to the British note<note n="45a" xml:id="d601fn45a">See telegram No. 111,
                        July 9, 7 p.m., to the Chargé in Italy, <ref target="#pg_729">p.
                        729</ref>.</note> the American Government will say that it intends to remain
                    aloof from the dispute and a State Department spokesman is quoted as declaring
                    that under no circumstances would the United States be party to sanctions
                    against Italy and that it would make no <pb facs="0830" n="728" xml:id="pg_728"
                    /> representations to the Italian Government. A report is also published that
                    the American Legion at Addis Ababa has been instructed to invite all Americans
                    to leave the country.</p>
                <p>No editorial comment with respect to the American attitude has yet appeared.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
